    <section id="the-problem" class="content-section">
      <h2>Why Multi-Condition Cases Are Different</h2>
      <p>Standard veterinary care is structured around individual conditions — one problem, one treatment, one specialist. When your cat has two, three, or four overlapping diagnoses, the system often isn't built to manage them together. Each specialist optimises for their condition. Nobody is necessarily optimising for the whole cat.</p>
      <p>Four of our cats have been complex multi-condition cases:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Minou</strong> — CKD and diabetes together, each complicating the management of the other</li>
        <li><strong>Artie</strong> — FIV, hyperthyroidism, asthma, and then neurological decline of unknown origin</li>
        <li><strong>Sorbet</strong> — CKD, FIV, hypertension, and hyperthyroidism, currently with limited appetite despite controlled thyroid numbers</li>
        <li><strong>Milton</strong> — CKD, arthritis, post-surgical orthopedic complications, and significant obesity that complicates every other treatment decision</li>
      </ul>
      <p>What these cases share: the right answer for one condition creates problems for another. Managing CKD and diabetes simultaneously means juggling conflicting dietary needs. Managing FIV alongside conditions requiring immunosuppressive treatment requires careful recalibration. Managing Milton's weight means calorie restriction in a CKD cat — which carries its own risks.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="interactions" class="content-section">
      <h2>Known Condition Interactions to Be Aware Of</h2>
      <div class="meds-list">
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">CKD + Hyperthyroidism</div>
          <div class="med-desc">Hyperthyroidism artificially inflates kidney blood flow, making CKD appear less severe than it is. Treating the thyroid can unmask kidney disease. Always trial methimazole before committing to permanent thyroid treatment — watch how creatinine responds. See the <a href="{{ '/conditions/hyperthyroidism/' | url }}">hyperthyroidism page</a> for detail.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">CKD + Diabetes</div>
          <div class="med-desc">Protein restriction for CKD can conflict with the high-protein diet recommended for diabetic cats. Dehydration from CKD can affect insulin absorption. Managing blood sugar in a cat who is also nauseous from uraemia is genuinely difficult. Work with your vet to find the least-bad compromise — there may not be a perfect answer.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">FIV + Conditions Requiring Steroids</div>
          <div class="med-desc">Both asthma and stomatitis are often managed with corticosteroids. In FIV-positive cats, systemic steroids further suppress an already compromised immune system. Inhaled steroids (for asthma) or cyclosporine (for stomatitis) may be preferable. Raise this specifically when steroids are recommended for an FIV-positive cat.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">Obesity + CKD</div>
          <div class="med-desc">Obesity worsens kidney disease, hypertension, and arthritis. But aggressive calorie restriction in a CKD cat risks muscle wasting and can worsen kidney function. Milton's situation requires slow, carefully monitored weight management — not a standard diet plan. Ask for a specific target weight and a realistic timeline.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">CKD + NSAIDs for Arthritis</div>
          <div class="med-desc">Non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) are commonly used for pain in cats with arthritis — but they are nephrotoxic and should not be used in cats with CKD except under very careful monitoring. If your cat has both arthritis and kidney disease, ask what pain management alternatives are appropriate. Solensia (frunevetmab), a newer injectable monoclonal antibody for feline arthritis pain, does not carry the same kidney risks.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="advocating" class="content-section">
      <h2>Advocating for the Whole Cat</h2>
      <p>In multi-condition cases, you often become the person holding the whole picture together — because no individual vet appointment covers it all. Some practical approaches:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Keep a single document with all current conditions, medications, and dosing.</strong> Bring it to every appointment. Update it after every change. This is especially important in emergency situations when you're dealing with a vet who doesn't know your cat's history.</li>
        <li><strong>Ask each specialist: "Given my cat's other conditions, are there any interactions or contraindications with what you're recommending?"</strong> They may not have the full picture unless you provide it.</li>
        <li><strong>Request that your various vets communicate with each other</strong> when making treatment changes that could affect other conditions. This doesn't always happen automatically.</li>
        <li><strong>Prioritise.</strong> In a complex case, you may not be able to manage every condition optimally at the same time. Work with your primary vet to decide which conditions are most urgent and which can be managed more conservatively.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="specialist" class="content-section">
      <h2>When to Push for a Specialist or Internal Medicine Consultation</h2>
      <p>A veterinary internal medicine specialist — often called an internist — is trained to manage complex multi-system disease. If your cat has three or more significant chronic conditions and you feel like nobody is seeing the whole picture, an internal medicine consultation is a reasonable ask.</p>
      <p>This doesn't mean your regular vet has failed. It means the complexity of the case has exceeded what a general practice is built to coordinate. Internal medicine specialists can often see interactions and options that aren't visible from a condition-by-condition view.</p>
      <div class="content-callout">
        <strong>In the US and Canada,</strong> veterinary internal medicine specialists are available at most referral hospitals and veterinary schools. Your regular vet can provide a referral, or you can call a specialist hospital directly to ask about a consultation. Cost is typically higher than a general practice visit — but a single consultation that identifies a key interaction or missed diagnosis can be worth significantly more.
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="vet-questions" class="content-section">
      <h2>Questions to Ask Your Vet</h2>
      <ul class="vet-questions">
        <li>Given all of my cat's conditions, are there any treatment interactions I should know about?</li>
        <li>Which of my cat's conditions is the most urgent priority right now?</li>
        <li>Is there any treatment you're recommending that is contraindicated by one of the other conditions?</li>
        <li>Should we consult a veterinary internist given the complexity of what we're managing?</li>
        <li>If we can't optimise everything, what's the least-bad approach overall?</li>
        <li>How are we balancing the management of condition A against the needs of condition B?</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

